<styl>crline <m0>From Herald Wire Services<ep>
   Steve Avery continued his strong pitching with a six-hitter and Chipper Jones hit a two-run homer Monday night to give the Atlanta Braves a 4-1 victory over the visiting Colorado Rockies.<ep>
   Avery (3-2) has allowed more than two runs in only one of his seven starts, showing he has returned to the form that led to 18-win seasons in 1991 and '93. He was 7-13 with a 4.67 ERA last season.<ep>
   Avery's only slipup came in the sixth inning after he retired the first two batters. Dante Bichette doubled down the left-field line and Larry Walker brought him home with a single to center.<ep>
   Other than that, Avery was masterful. He had a season-high nine strikeouts, walked no one, and other than the sixth, never gave up more than one hit in an inning. Plus, Bichette's double was the only extra-base hit by the power-hitting Rockies. Avery threw 101 pitches in his first complete game of the season.<ql>
